body:
Currently we're bumping version numbers with following rules:
- for Electron API breakage, bump major version;
- for major Chrome upgrades, minor Node upgrades, significant Electron changes, behavior changes, bump minor version;
- for new features and bug fixes, bump patch version;

So no, we are not following semver in Electron for now. We only guarantee there is no API changes between major version bumps, but Chrome and Node.js updates can still introduce breaking changes.

Currently for nearly every release of Electron, we are adding lots of things. If we follow semver strictly, the version number of Electron would be something like 32.15.0. I don't think it is better than what we have now, from current version number of Electron you can know:
- every patch version bump means bug fixes and new things, it is safe to upgrade;
- minor version bumps are dangerous, your app is supposed to still work, but you have to check carefully for possible breaks;
- major version bump means there are API changes of Electron, and you have to modify your app to run with it.

I think the root problem is we are adding new too fast, and publishing new releases too frequently. The only time when a new release only includes fixes is when we back-port fixes to old versions, or hot-fixing the latest release, which rarely happens. So following semver becomes meaningless in our case.

We should probably document explicitly that we are not following semver, and people should always use fixed version number.

@jbenet Adding a number is a big deal. When in doubt, use community standards. Electron is built on Node and npm, electron-prebuilt is distributed via npm, so I think it's wise to go with the [established standards](https://docs.npmjs.com/getting-started/semantic-versioning). A project with a `package.json` should respect the consequences of changing the version number w/r/t the default way that packages are added via `npm install --save`. Running `npm install electron-prebuilt --save` yields:

```
{
  ...
  "dependencies": {
    "electron-prebuilt": "^1.1.0"
  }
}
```

The `^` has implications that rely on a project adhering to semantic versioning. Marketing concerns should not be the primary driver when responsibly versioning a software product that is used exclusively by node developers.

@feross

The named OS X releases include their proper version number distinctions, like "10.10" and "10.11", which form a vital part of major compatibility barriers for thousands of developers building for OS X. "Things should work" but often major breaking problems happen, and the effort required for a dramatic change like that is much larger than every time a single breaking change is committed. this applies to Electron.

"end users" there includes developers. There are different kinds of developers, with different kinds of expectations for versions. "I want to know the difference between a v1 and a v2, and that's not captured by semver" is something i've heard dozens (maybe hundreds?) of times from other developers. This is not all, but a sizable number of the people who know the value of semver and still choose not use it. 

---

@ungoldman please re-read. I'm strongly in favor of Electron using semver and packing exactly according to semver. I'm suggesting a compromise that enables the Electron team to layer any non-semver expectations separately.
